<h2>Let's see something cool</h2>
<p class="text">Let's say you wanted to render some text and truncate it to one line. Well you could easily get this done with CSS but we can do the following:</p>

{{code-snippet name="example6.hbs"}}

{{line-clamp
  classNames="example"
  text=text
  lines=1
  interactive=false
}}

<p class="text">If you inspect the above text you will see that it uses <pre style="display: inline;">text-overflow: ellipsis;</pre>. The interactive flag prevents the truncation from being interactive as we will see later.</p>

<p class="text">Let's increase the lines to 4</p>

{{code-snippet name="example7.hbs"}}

{{line-clamp
  classNames="example"
  text=text
  lines=4
  interactive=false
}}

<p class="text">If you are using Chrome you will notice that <pre style="display: inline">-webkit-line-clamp: 4;</pre> is used. If you are not on Chrome it will use JS to truncate the text to the specified number of lines.</p>

<p class="text">Let's force JS in Chrome as well by using the <pre style="display: inline">useJsOnly=true</pre>.</p>

{{code-snippet name="example8.hbs"}}

{{line-clamp
  classNames="example"
  text=text
  lines=4
  interactive=false
  useJsOnly=true
}}

